`docs/` holds the normative reference material for `crates/steno` — the
`.steno` source-format spec, the compile-pipeline description, and the
TS→Rust porting record. Nothing here is compiled; these files are the
contract that the parser, expander, renderer, and test corpus must stay
consistent with, and are what an editor should update *first* when a
pass boundary, directive, or corpus fixture changes, then verify against
the actual code.

The three files describe adjacent slices of the same pipeline and must
stay mutually consistent when one changes: `steno-format.md` is the
authority on source syntax (fences, directives, template operators,
stroke key order) and explicitly cedes ground truth to the parser code
when they disagree; `pipeline.md` picks up immediately after parsing and
owns pass ordering, the `Behaviors`/editor model, and the error
taxonomy, and explicitly defers back to `steno-format.md` for expansion-
time semantics of `%d`/`%[…%]`/`%(…)` and `@literal`. Both agree on the
seven directives and on `@fuse`'s effect of merging the entry's last
stroke into the first appended type stroke — a change to `@fuse`
semantics in code must be reflected in both docs. `porting-notes.md` is
the arbiter for corpus/test divergences from the TS reference (the
`STKWR-FB` fence fix, `STKWR-LT`'s repurposing) — its resolutions are
precedent, not open questions, and reverting `dict.steno` or
`blocks.rs`'s `@literal` emitter to "match" the old TS behavior would
silently reopen closed divergences.

Any change to pass boundaries, directive semantics, `Behaviors` presets,
or error types in `crates/steno/src` needs a matching edit in
`pipeline.md` and/or `steno-format.md`; any change to `dict.steno`'s
`STKWR-FB`/`STKWR-LT` entries needs a check against `porting-notes.md`'s
documented resolutions before landing.